<TEXT>
a federal appeals court has agreed to 
reconsider its decision ordering the nations space agency to 
release the audio tape recording of space shuttle astronauts 
moments before they died in the 1986 challenger disaster 
the full us circuit court of appeals granted the governments 
request for a rehearing of the case by all of its 11 members 
the decision contained in an oct 5 order made public friday 
came two months after a split panel of three appellate judges ruled 
the tapes of the jan 28 1986 shuttle disaster should be made 
public under the freedom of information act 
the national aeronautics and space administration has refused to 
give up the tapes contending their release would subject the 
survivors of the seven astronauts to emotional stress when they are 
played repeatedly on radio and television 
two members of the courts liberal wing spottswood robinson iii 
and harry edwards joined in the july 29 ruling that drew a 
blistering dissent from circuit judge douglas h ginsburg a member 
of the courts 65 conservative majority 
the brief order granting the petition for a rehearing en banc 
stated only that a majority of the 11 judges had agreed to 
reconsider the earlier decision 
the order said a briefing schedule would be announced later 
a nasa spokeswoman patricia m riep praised the decision 
friday evening 
</TEXT>
