<TEXT>
when the 100th congress began the district of 
columbia dreamed of becoming the nations 51st state but as 
congress winds down almost two years later the dream has ended and 
the nations capital is hoping to hold on to whatever limited 
selfgovernance it has 
somehow the district became entangled in four touchy issues 
abortion rights life insurance for aids victims homosexual rights 
and a residency requirement for city workers 
in all four congress has told the city to change its laws or 
lose the money the federal government provides as a payment for the 
cost incurred in being the seat of the federal government 
those actions stunned city officials especially walter 
fauntroy the local clergyman who serves as the districts 
nonvoting delegate in the house of representatives he accused 
colleagues of exerting raw naked power over the city 
it is unfair to single out the district of columbia and tell 
them how to spend local funds fumes fauntroy that violates 
the letter and spirit of home rule 
adds julius hobson the citys chief lobbyist to congress by 
taking these actions the congress has in effect created the us 
department of the district of columbia the floodgates have been 
opened after this what next 
fauntroy had bragged he would force a vote on the house floor on 
the statehood issue by last july 4 he was wrong and he now 
concedes the issue may not even come up for a vote in the 101st 
congress which begins its twoyear run in january 
under the limited home rule law enacted by congress in 1974 
congress approves the citys budget home rule gave the citys 
670000 residents the right to elect a mayor and city council but 
left them without a vote in congress and provided a congressional 
veto of laws enacted by the city council congress has exercised 
the veto only twice before 
this years city budget is 32 billion including 539 million 
in federal money which is supposed to be a payment in lieu of 
taxes on real estate owned by the federal government and foreign 
governments 
on the demand of conservatives congress attached amendments to 
the appropriations bill and president reagan signed them into law 
last weekend 
one provides that the city couldnt pay for any abortions except 
to save the life of the mother in the past eight years the 
district government paid for 32725 abortions 
another amendent demanded that the city repeal a law requiring 
insurance companies to sell life insurance to people with aids a 
third insisted the city revamp its human rights code under which 
georgetown university has been required to grant rights to gay 
student groups 
a fourth told the city to soften its law requiring most city 
employees to live within the districts boundaries 
the city just happened to be a victim on the issues of 
abortion and gay rights said sen charles grassley riowa who 
sided with the city on those questions the city became a 
battleground for two larger social issues it just happened to be 
there at the wrong time 
meanwhile the statehood quest championed by fauntroy has 
bogged down over questions about whether congress would still pay 
the city in exchange for lost tax revenues 
senate republicans would be sure to oppose statehood out of 
recognition that the heavilydemocratic state of new columbia 
almost certainly would be represented by two democratic senators 
congressional approval of statehood would only be the first 
step a constitutional amendment would have to be approved by 
threequarters of the states before it could take effect 
in the past reagan has threatened to veto the districts 
spending package if it did not include abortion language similar to 
the restriction proposed by rep robert dornan rcalif 
however reagan was prevented from doing so because the city 
budget was often lumped with several other appropriation measures 
into a single bill vetoing it would have denied federal agencies 
of funds 
fauntry said adoption this time of a separate bill dealing with 
district of columbia spending left the city vulnerable to prolife 
and antigay forces in congress 
while fauntroy has threatened to encourage city officials to 
disobey the congressional orders and city council chairman david 
clarke has called for citizens of the nations capital to take to 
the streets in protest mayor marion barry jr surprised many 
washingtonians by remaining aloof 
this vote is not a direct attack on home rule barry said 
after all they did approve every penny of our appropriations 
bill the district bill was just used as a vehicle by special 
interest groups on electionyear issues 
fauntroy said he is considering filing lawsuits and initiating 
nonviolent protests to challenge the congressional action clarke 
said his sworn oath to uphold the constitution would prevent him 
from restricting abortion funding or changing the human rights code 
