<TEXT>
a huge archive of longsecret documents 
of a family powerful in italy during the renaissance has been 
acquired by yale university and may give scholars a better 
understanding of 15th and 16thcentury europe 
the spinelli family were bankers and businessmen who held 
important offices in the florentine state family members also were 
generals in wars between italian citystates treasurers to popes 
spies and ambassadors the familys activities spanned four 
centuries 
the family even had business offices in rome venice barcelona 
lyons and london 
yale announced saturday that it obtained the collection in april 
through a swiss rare books dealer yale spokesman walter littell 
said he didnt know how much yale paid for it and said no further 
information would be made available about the deal 
the collection obtained by yales beinecke rare book and 
manuscript library comprises more than 150000 detailed records and 
chronicles that have never been studied by scholars and are 
virtually unknown to historians yale said 
the documents are among the most significant of any known 
italian archive said yale president benno c schmidt jr 
ralph w franklin beinecke director said the collection 
includes records of banking activities international trade and 
finance family life marriage slavery inheritance private 
wealth and patronage of charitable organizations 
the records also include detailed information about the business 
concerns of other families including the medicis and borgias 
i do not think history books on the period will be written 
again without mentioning the spinelli the spinellis relationships 
with the medici are well documented and the families even 
intermarried but the spinelli represent a completely different 
faction of florentine politics said robert g babcock the 
librarys edwin j beinecke curator of early books and manuscipts 
yale officials said the most significant document found in the 
collection is a 1440 record by tommaso spinelli treasurer for 
several popes in the 15th century it is his record of tax payments 
to the vatican by every diocese and abbey in the world and 
codifies the financial state of the church under eugenius iv who 
was pope from 14311447 
yale said it could take as long as four years to complete 
cataloging the documents some of them might be made available to 
scholars as early as january and an exhibition of some of the 
documents will open at the university in may 
</TEXT>
