<TEXT>
violent riots sweeping this north 
african arab nation grew out of years of frustration with the rigid 
socialist system and a declining economy that has created a growing 
crowd of jobless youth 
the precise motives and causes of different groups of rioters in 
the past several days have been difficult to disentangle 
a shadowy islamic fundamentalist movement on saturday said it 
started the unrest and warned it would unleash even greater 
violence unless its demands are met 
the previously unknown movement for algerian renewal 
presented a series of demands including satisfying the immediate 
needs of the population and replacing the government of president 
chadli bendjedid 
since a 1965 military coup algeria has been under a stern 
sovietstyle government the constitution declares islam the state 
religion but says socialism is the only path to independence 
the revolt began tuesday with spontaneous acts of violence by 
youngsters without any distinct political or social cause their 
slogans attacked the high cost of living and the fat cats 
living in luxury but they offered no remedies some chants 
supported competing algerian soccer teams 
moslem fundamentalists recognizable in the fastliving capital 
by their beards and flowing white robes began taking over the 
movement thursday small groups of them were seen taking the lead 
of violent crowds and pointing out the luxury stores and 
restaurants for the wealthy as suitable targets for the masses 
wrath 
but later the moslems were seen reasoning with the crowd and 
encouraging them to disperse peacefully 
with the armys tanks and armored personnel carriers deployed at 
strategic points throughout the capital and troops with fixed 
bayonets ready to shoot to maintain public order the older and 
more experienced fundamentalists had no difficulty getting their 
point across 
on saturday they flung off the veil and proclaimed themselves 
the leaders of the movement of revolt in a statement 
distributed to news organizations 
but it was not known whether the islamic fundamentalists 
actually set the protests in motion or were rushing to the front to 
try to lead the parade in the direction they preferred 
so far the fundamentalist movement is alone in its attempt to 
make political capital out of the revolt 
no one has demanded a limitation of the soaring birthrate or 
measures to cope with unemployment which has reached 40 percent in 
the larger cities the fundamentalists have been reluctant to 
address these deeper causes of popular discontent 
their demand for the removal of the government did not include 
the ouster of bendjedid personally falling in line with the 
widespread feeling that responsibility for the regimes failures 
lies not with the president but with the fat cats conspiring to 
obstruct his policies 
the president has been the main advocate of an economic 
austerity program permitting algeria to live within its means 
during a period of low prices for oil and gas which make up 97 
percent of algerias exports 
nearly 60 percent of algerias 25 million people are less than 
20 years old in the middle of the demographic explosion bendjedid 
has fought opposition within the national liberation front the 
only legal party to move away from a strictly governmentdirected 
economy 
under the austerity program prices on many formerly subsidized 
goods have risen 40 percent since january a block of butter that 
cost 50 cents 10 months ago for example now costs almost a dollar 
on saturday the army continued to move troops into the major 
cities and the military command issued repeated warnings for 
people to remain off the streets 
shopkeepers took no chances and began lowering curtains and 
barring shop fronts shortly after noon on saturday algeria 
operates on an islamic week and saturday and sunday are normally 
working days 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
michael goldsmith the north africa 
correspondent for the associated press has been covering events in 
algeria for the past 20 years 
</TEXT>
