here is the text of saturdays democratic 
radio address by sen daniel p moynihan dny 
this is senator pat moynihan of new york and im here to 
present the democratic response to president reagans weekly radio 
address 
this past year has been one of considerable even historic 
bipartisan cooperation here in the nations capital we have sent 
the president a hugely important trade bill catastrophic health 
insurance and after onehalf century at long last welfare reform 
mr president youve invited me to the rose garden thursday 
afternoon when youll sign the welfare bill and so ill see you 
then but this is the last time we will have this exchange on a 
saturday so i would like to talk about one last great bipartisan 
effort we could have together 
this is the omnibus drug bill which we introduced in the senate 
on monday today you talked about the house bill ill talk about 
the senate bill may i say we surprised ourselves over the last 
few years as the most recent drug epidemic has spread across the 
nation there have been all too familiar efforts to make this a 
partisan issue as if one party knew more about how to cope with 
the emergency or cared more or would spend more or would punish 
more or just plain demagogue more most of which ended in 
stalemate and namecalling 
this time we decided we could do better in may senate majority 
leader robert c byrd appointed me and senator nunn of georgia to 
head a democratic working group senate republican leader bob dole 
appointed senators rudman damato wilson and gramm to do 
likewise the two groups met and we learned to our surprise just 
how much we agreed 
first we agreed that there is an epidemic it is primarily 
associated with crack a derivative of cocaine which first 
appeared in the bahamas in 1983 by 1985 it had reached new york 
city by 1986 kansas city and then across the country since then 
hospital emergency room admissions due to illicit drugs have 
increased tenfold 
one half of all juveniles in detention at this moment are the 
result of drugrelated crimes almost half of juveniles arrested 
have been arrested at least five times we agreed that the federal 
government has a major responsibility here these drugs come into 
the country illegally if the federal government did not prevent 
their entry it must help with their aftermath 
first then a drug czar a member of the cabinet to lead this 
effort next a real effort our interdiction program is pathetic 
when you think what is needed when we started the drug enforcement 
administration we created some 2100 special agents fifteen years 
later there are not quite 2900 federal aid to street law 
enforcement has all but disappeared there are not nearly enough 
federal prosecutors or federal prisons 
above all there is almost no federal support for treatment we 
dont know much about treatment for crack but we do know that 
young people who get into drugs soon wish they could get out and 
there are millions of them one american in 10 has used an illicit 
drug in the last month clearly we must provide treatment on 
request whatever you do in an epidemic you dont close your 
hospitals 
and so mr president on monday we introduced a bipartisan 
600page 26 billion drug bill it marks a major departure in 
federal policy we allocate 40 percent of funds to the supply side 
which is to say programs such as crop eradication and border 
interdiction there is a death penalty eviction forfeiture a 
threetime loser life sentence 
but 60 percent of the funds go to the demand side testing 
education treatment senator byrd and senator dole are the lead 
sponsors among the many cosponsors you will find senator quayle 
and senator bentsen 
we need your help we have four legislative days left in the 
100th congress we cant pass the house bill it has just too many 
extras some of which you mentioned but we can pass the senate 
bill and the house will take a clean bill and so i would ask mr 
president send word that you will sign the senate bill and well 
get it to your desk and so good day good luck to us all 
