<TEXT>
a papyrus boat paddled by a sixmember 
greek crew set out saturday from this aegean port to recreate a 
10000yearold voyage to the island of melos 
a blackrobed bishop chanted a 20minute blessing and a band 
played music to begin the archaeological experiment to determine 
how stone age seafarers would have made the 94mile trip 
several thousand people applauded as the 21foot open boat 
named papyrela for the greek word for papyrus and made of yellow 
papyrus stems lashed together with rope slipped away from the 
dockside at sunset 
the islandhopping voyage to melos will take eight or nine days 
if the weather is favorable said elias mamounas captain of the 
papyrela 
a greek navy vessel and a yacht will escort the boat said haris 
tzalas head of the hellenic institute for the preservation of 
nautical tradition which organized the project 
the earliest known mediterranean seafarers went to melos to 
obtain supplies of obsidian a volcanic glass prized in ancient 
times as a razorsharp cutting tool 
american archaeologists found obsidian blades during excavations 
in the 1970s at the franchthi cave in southern greece they 
belonged to mesolithic cave dwellers and were dated to around 8000 
bc 
boats made of papyrus a kind of reed also were used in ancient 
egypt from about 5000 bc the norwegian explorer thor heyerdahl 
sailed from egypt across the atlantic in a papyrus boat the rai 
