dean burk a retired chief chemist at the 
national cancer institute died of cancer at the home of his 
daughter in washington he was 84 
dr burk who was cytochemistry chief at the nci laboratory 
where he had worked for more than 30 years before retiring in 1974 
received the hildebrand prize in 1952 for his work on 
photosynthesis the process by which plants make starch and sugar 
from air and water with the aid of sunlight 
he died thursday 
the gerhard domagk prize was awarded to him in 1965 for his 
development of procedures for distinguishing the difference between 
a normal cell and one damaged by cancer 
he was the codeveloper of the prototype of the magnetic 
resonance scanner an imagining device frequently used instead of 
