<TEXT>
electricity customers in chicago are paying the 
highest rates in the united states this fall a utility watchdog 
group said 
a citizens utility board study concluded electric rates charged 
by commonwealth edison co are increasing an average 62 percent as 
rates are converted from summer to winter scales this month 
edison serves chicago and much of northern illinois 
the increase approved by the illinois commerce commission in 
june means that a typical monthly residential bill will be 5858 
according to the study 
after chicago the next most expensive american cities for 
nonsummer electric rates were philadelphia with an average of 
5257 new york at 4966 san diego at 4539 and phoenix at 
4139 the study said 
an edison spokesman said the study results are misleading 
because a 13 percent reduction in summer rates is not considered 
the study figures were based on an estimate of 400 kilowatt 
hours per month by a singlefamily or twofamily building that does 
not have electric heat 
theyre not giving us credit for the rate reduction that was 
in effect during the hottest summer in history people paid 
substantially less than they would have if the old rates were in 
effect said edison spokesman john hogan 
the illinois commerce commission approved the 62 percent jump in 
winter rates as an emergency measure to reduce the difference 
between summer and winter bills 
